Activities.Validation activities: Verify that the model documentation describes the objective(s) of and reason(s) for the model (re) development, including the main model modifications compared to the incumbent model.
Activities.Comments: no incumbent model mentioned in the document

Activities.Validation activities: Verify that the model documentation clearly describes the model scope as defined for model development and the range of application, in terms of KB legal entities, client types, regions and/or countries, product types, industries.
Activities.Comments: client types, which parts of the KB will use the model - not clarified

Activities.Validation activities:
Verify that the model documentation describes the relevant business practices such as but not limited to:

- Business strategy (incl. e.g. growth ambitions for the portfolio, risk appetite),
- Acceptance criteria,
- Any procedures for overrides and appeals,
- Description of the limit-setting approach and/or affordability calculation,
- Monitoring and EWS processes in place.

Note that the model documentation can also refer to other existing documents (e.g. Retail Credit Risk Policy) that describe the relevant practices.
Activities.Comments: business strategy, monitoring and EWS processes are not clarified

Activities.Validation activities:
Verify that the model documentation describes the sampling approach and dataset generation, including training, out-of-time validation, out-of-sample validation and reject inference datasets where applicable.

Verify that the model documentation describes results of relevant representativeness analyses.
Activities.Comments: reject inference and out-of-sample validation was not applied

Activities.Validation activities:
Verify that the model documentation describes in detail the model design, including but not limited to:

- Model assumptions (or reference to academic papers explaining the theory),
- Choice of modelling approach and algorithm (e.g. traditional vs. machine-learning approaches, which machine-learning algorithms to use),
- Target variable definition,
- Variable selection and transformation,
- Model estimation,
- If applicable, reject inference approach,
- Any implicit and explicit model assumptions,
- Use of external data and model-based (external and internal) inputs,
- Use of human judgement in the model development process.
Activities.Comments: modelling approach are not clarified, the purpose of choosing models are not mentioned

Activities.Validation activities: Verify that the model documentation describes the modelling approach, including the conceptual model structure and the final model structure (including factor weights/feature importance for ML models).
Activities.Comments: only tree-based models were trained, other models are not evaluated

Activities.Validation activities:
For TPM only:

Verify that the model documentation:
- Contains at least overview of the data used for the model development,
- Describes principles of the model design and modelling methods,
- Describes target variable definition,
- Contains model performance results.

For TPM only:

if the model was developed more than 12 months before the start of the validation, verify that monitoring reports are available.

For models with planned periodic refits:

Verify that the model documentation clearly describes the model refit procedure including the intended frequency, triggers, methodology and business rationale behind the model refit.

For models with planned periodic refits:

Verify that computer codes necessary to perform the refit are properly documented, i.e. they contain clear inventory of scripts and order of running them together with necessary input datasets and the description of output datasets. Also verify that the codes and accompanying documentation have substantial information needed to perform the model retraining exercise independently.

Verify that the scope (segments, products, customers, etc.) at model development and the scope at model application are consistent, i.e. the model is not used for a scope where it was not designed to be used.

Verify that the historical data period used is appropriate. In particular, consider if:

- The data period is sufficiently long to build a robust model, e.g. in terms of number of defaults, 
- The data period contains material changes in market conditions, credit process and risk appetite that may affect the model.

Verify that the use of data is compliant with KB policies and external regulations. Verify correct data usage with Data Stewards.

Verify that the use of data is compliant with KB policies and external regulations, ensuring that all external sources are reliable and trustworthy. Confirm correct data usage with Data Stewards.

Verify that the data transformations are appropriate given the modelling approach and the potential risk of overfitting (e.q. monotonicity of target variable realization rate is enforced for Weight of Evidence or other optimal binning-based transformations).

Data transformations include:

- Standardization
- Winsorization (i.e. capping and flooring)
- Functional transformations (e.g. Weight of Evidence, line-fitting using target variable, mapping to numeric scale, etc.).

Verify that data transformations are also applied in an identical manner to the model testing and application data.
Verify that missing target variable values are not material in terms of percentage of missing values as per measurement period (typically below 1%*).

Verify that per variable in the final model, the percentage of missing values is not material (typically below 10%).

Note that the 10% threshold excludes missing values due to structural reasons (e.g. clients that do not have credit bureau record or existing relationship with KB will have missing credit bureau and behavioural variables).
Verify that the percentage of missing values as per measurement period for the model estimate  (e.g. score, estimated income) is not material.

Analyze the percentage of duplicates in the unique identifier (e.g. customer ID, application ID, combination of customer ID and application date, etc.) in the model development dataset for initial validation and in the validation dataset for full review and periodic validation,  ensuring that the threshold for duplicates is less than 1%

Where applicable, also consider the use of additional identification attributes to check for duplicates, e.g. tax registration ID.

Verify that the number of invalid values for all data fields used to define the target variable are not material in terms of percentage of invalid values as per measurement period.

Invalid values can include: Unexpected values, missing values and outliers, e.g. non-numeric or negative arrears or DPD values, default or fraud flag other than 0, 1 or indeterminate, etc.

Verify that the number of invalid variable values in the final model is not significant in terms of the percentage of invalid values during the measurement period, considering the variable's importance in the model. 

- For continuous variables: compute general statistics (mean, median, mode, standard deviation, quantiles) for the variable and ensure that the ranges align with expectations.
- For categorical variable in the final model, check the distribution of outcomes and verify that these are in line with expectations.

Verify that the model estimates can be replicated over the observation period (randomly pick the estimates, manually calculate the prediction/score and compare with the estimates provided)

Verify that the model estimate (e.g. score) is within expected range.
Assess the timeliness of any triggers and data fields used to construct the target variable (e.g. daily vs. month-end DPD counts)

Verify that all data required for the development or validation of the model are stored and are readily available and accessible.

Also check that the data needed for model use will be available going forward (relevant especially for any external data, upstream model inputs).

Verify that a data collection plan is created with clear instructions by the model owner and data provider roles assigned in order to meet the data needs for regular model monitoring, periodic validations and full reviews on an ongoing basis.

Verify (via random selection) over time that the target variables have been correctly constructed given the raw information from the data sources.


In classification models random selection need to be performed both  for "0" and "1" target values (reject inference should be checked seperately as well).

E.g.:
- 90+_6m target variable value need to be checked with the overdue days
- Default_flag variable value need to be checked with the all Default criteria.

Verify (via random selection) over time that the independed variables have been correctly constructed given the raw information from the data sources.


E.g.:
- PTI (payment to income) variable value need to be checked having the monthly payments and monthly average salary
- Max_DPD_6m (max days past due in the last 6 months) variable value need to be checked in the banking system.

- Verify that the target variable definition is correctly implemented in the model development (or production) datasets.
- Assess whether the target variable definition is representative of what the model intends to predict, (e.g. 'technical positive target definition flag' are excluded).

Verify that the target variable is appropriate for the model and properly substantiated with analysis and argumentation.

For acceptance scorecards, verify that deviations from the Definition of Default are properly justified with supporting analysis and argumentation on, e.g.:

- (during initial validation) Business intuition, especially in terms of significant decline in creditworthiness and process implications (e.g. Do the alternative default triggers such as 60 DPD signal sufficient deterioration in creditworthiness? Do they correspond to differentiation in client treatment, such as watchlisting, early collection activities, etc.?)

- (during initial validation) Choice of performance window, based on vintage analysis to understand the realization of target flags over time (e.g. for Mortgages and SME portfolios, as defaults are not expected to occur within the first 12 months, a longer performance window is typically considered.)

- Alignment with planned model use, especially in term of cut-off setting, and any associated need for calibration
- Resulting number and proportion of defaults under different trigger (e.g. 60 DPD vs. 90 DPD)
performance window (e.g. 12 months vs. 24 months vs. 36 months) and materiality threshold (e.g. EUR 500 vs. EUR 0) options
- Evidence of strong correlation between the alternative target variable definition and the Definition of Default as defined in the Global Definition of Default policy
- Inclusion vs. exclusion of observations that have not completed the performance window but already defaulted (where standard treatment is exclusion of observations that have not completed the performance window)
Replicate the scripts used for development (or recalibration) and verify the results. Store the replication dataset and scripts in the shareable format (e.g., DataIku bundle).

Activities.Sub Dimension type: Model Methodology, Structure and Modelling choice
Activities.Validation activities:
Assess the appropriateness of the model structure and components given, e.g.:

- Intended use of the model and integration into the processes
- Applicable methodology standards
- Available data sources

Ensure that the model development have been conducted under the regulatory requirements (if exists e.g. IRB requirements or IFRS standards) and/or model development methodology/standards.
Verify the significance of the estimated Variable weights (p-value <5%).

Verify that a sufficient share of the model development data has been saved for OOS and OOT testing, typically in the range of 5-30%, depending on the size of the model development data (considering e.g. the total number of defaults).

If k-fold cross validation or bootstrapping techniques have been used instead of OOS testing, verify that the use of these approaches is justified (e.g. due to data limitations).

If OOT testing was not performed, verify that this was justified (e.g. due to data limitations) and alternative approaches were considered (e.g. approach similar to k-fold cross-validation, keeping one year out at a time).

Verify that OOS testing, k-fold cross-validation, bootstrapping and/or regularization techniques have been used to avoid overfitting and strike the right balance between bias vs. variance trade-off.

A decline of >5-10% Gini (~2.5-5% AUC) on test (i.e. validation) vs. train sample can be indicative of overfitting.

Assess the appropriateness of the performance metrics used to evaluate the model performance during model build (e.g. K-S statistic, prioritisation of false positives vs. false negatives, confusion matrices around the cut-off region, etc.).

Assess whether the cost of Type ll errors, i.e. 'false negatives has been considered in setting the discriminatory threshold.

Verify that pairwise correlations between variables included in the model are below the acceptable threshold, where values below 0.5 are considered acceptable (green), between 0.5 and 0.7 indicate moderate correlation (yellow), and above 0.7 are considered high.
Verify that the Variance Inflation Factor of the model is below the acceptable threshold.

For models with planned periodic refits:

- Check the testing result of the approach with recent data to assess the variability of algorithmic updates.

- Check whether manual steps are required for each update of the model, and if the procedure, output and the scope of the manual intervention are clearly defined.

- Check the justification of why an algorithmic update is used instead of a fixed model

- Verify that input data that will be used in the model retraining (refit) exercises is clearly described in terms of timespan, also ensure that original scoping of the model as well as all exclusions, knock out rules and data treatments used in the initial model development will remain in the periodic refit.

- Ensure that necessary data quality controls for input datasets needed to perform the model refit exist at least to the same extent as for the input data used for the original model development.

- Ensure that consistent methodology for measuring model output performance of refitted models is set in place and described in the monitoring plan. Also verify that adequate controls exist to ensure the metrics do not exhibit significant declining performance with the refitted model.

Verify that whole rating systems (i.e. capital models):

- were used/considered during the model development process,
- are used in the underwriting process (e.g. as KO-rules, for risk based pricing, as a Variable in the model or combined in the final model scores).

If the ratings are not used, verify if appropriate justification is available.

Ensure that statistical information sources (such as training and calibration datasets) adequately represent the different phases of the economic cycle, as required. For instance, IRB and IFRS models necessitate data that encompasses various economic cycles.
Check whether calibration is conducted based on methodology

Verify that signs of the estimated Variable weights are in line with business intuition (for machine learning models - Shap values/feature effects), considering impact of normalization and any transformations in the assessment.
Check whether business interpretation of Variables was assessed during model development and/or during working group

Compute and plot AUC as per measurement period and over full history for the overall model, as well as by sub-models (e.g. behavioural scorecard) where applicable.

Where the number of target variable realizations is not sufficient to allow robust AUC calculations, MV may refer to the confidence interval around the AUC (calculated using asymptotical normality assumption, using the standard error estimate) to motivate the severity of any findings.
Based on the final model output, calculate the AUC as per measurement period and over full history for significant segments (e.g. industry, country, region, product type, size, maturity).
Calculate AUC as per measurement period and over full history for individual Variables.
Assess discriminatory power (AUC) of the model on the basis of the available documentation and compare the results with the calculations conducted by MV (activities above).

"Compute and plot the following metrics (depending on relevancy):

- Cross-sectional Analysis (e.g. Income estimation)
- Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE)
- Adjusted R²
- Spearman correlation (used instead of Pearson correlation to better capture monotonic relationships and reduce sensitivity to outliers or non-linearities; evaluated using the following thresholds: < 0.5 = red, 0.5–0.7 = yellow, > 0.7 = green)
- gAUC

Time Series Analysis (e.g. Stress test models)
- Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE)
- Adjusted R² (only for stationary time series)
- Spearman correlation (preferred for non-parametric relationships; thresholds: < 0.5 = red, 0.5–0.7 = yellow, > 0.7 = green)
gAUC
- Theil-U statistics (optional)

These metrics should be computed between estimated and realised target variable as per measurement period and over full history for the overall model as well as by sub-models where applicable.This calculation should be done both before and after any overlays/overrides."

Based on the final model output, calculate the metrics mentioned above as per measurement period and over full history for significant segments (e.g. industry, country, region, product type, size, maturity).
Compute performance metrics (e.g Adj-R2, MAPE)  as per measurement period and over full history for individual Variables.

Compute performance metrics (e.g Adj-R2, MAPE)  between the model outputs and the realized target variable values per measurement period and over full history for individual Variables and specific segments.
Assess performance metrics (e.g Adj-R2, MAPE) of the model on the basis of the available documentation and compare the results with the calculations conducted by MV (activities above).

If the actual prediction level (e.g. PD) is used:

Calculate and plot realised and estimated target variable (e.g. default rate, income, fraud rate) as per measurement period at portfolio level/based on modelling sample. Where applicable and material, also include sub-models in the graphs.

Estimated and target variables need to be compared via Binomal test using 95% Confidence Interval.

As an alternative approach, 95% Confidence Intervals around observed target rate are computed using Jeffrey's interval, following the same distributional assumptions as specified for Validation activity #2 in this section (test statistic computation).

Verify that any scaling approaches have been applied correctly (if needed, e.g. due to over-sampling).

Compute t-test to compare the means of the predicted values and the actual values. 

Using the statistical (hypothesis - 95% Confidence Internval) test confirm whether the actual and estimated values are close to each other. The analysis should be performed at least on portfolio and bucket levels.

Assess the PiT calibration quality of the overall PD (or LGD/EAD) at portfolio level and/or at sub-model level where applicable:

- Conduct the PiT backtests on the full economic cycle. Calculate the number weighted and exposure weighted mis-estimations.

Compute the Population Stability Index (PSI) for the model output distribution overall (divide into 10 buckets of equal width), comparing the model output distribution for each observation quarter with the distribution at development or at the earliest available observation quarter. Also plot the distribution.

Where relevant and material, perform the analyses on sub-model level.

If results are below thresholds (Red), perform #6

Identify for which purposes the model output is used, including but not limited to:

- Cut-off setting
- Policy rules
- Monitoring (Risk-based) pricing
- Limit setting
- Elasticity models
- Early Warning Signal models

Assess whether the model satisfies the business requirements for the various intended purposes and whether the final model is in line with business logic.

For TPM only:

Confirm the necessity to use external model (e.g. insufficient internal data available due to low-default nature of the portfolio or new entry to market).
